K-Means Clustering

Clustering identifies groupings within unlabeled data.

The k-means algorithm works by placing points into clusters and computing their centroids, which is defined as the average of the data points in the cluster. Each data point is assigned to one cluster.

This example uses the NBA statistics from 2008 to cluster players based on their stats and not explicitly defined groups.

# define 5 clusters
k5 <- kmeans(nba, centers=5,nstart = 25)

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
nba %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate(cluster = k5$cluster,
         player = row.names(nba)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(PTS,G,color = factor(cluster), label = player)) +
  geom_text()+
  theme_minimal()

Visualize cluster for Average Number of Points (PTS) and Number of games played during the season (G).
